Ways to create String

//1.String Literals
String str = "Selenium";

//2. new keyword
String str = new String("Selenium");

String is always stored in a special section of Heap Memory called String Constant Pool[SCP]
SCP cannot hold duplicate values
==> If a string is created using string literals, both == & equals give the same result

== compares the memory address of the objects[== compares the objects]
equals() This compares the value of the objects

String immutability [that cannot be changed]

If you  know string might have to be changed ....you should avoid creating String class to create String.
In such cases, Java has provided us with additional Classes:
-StringBuffer
-StringBuilder
